edk2-nvidia's DeviceTree.inf pseudo-module preprocesses .dts files with
"cpp -x assembler-with-cpp -undef -imacros AutoGen.h ...". AutoGen.h
transitively includes this header. In assembler-with-cpp mode, GCC's
preprocessor treats "defined(__has_feature)" as true (it's recognized
enough to satisfy defined()) but doesn't support actually *calling*
__has_feature(...)/__has_builtin(...) as a function-like operator - so
once let inside, GCC hits a hard parse error:

  Base.h:63:23: error: missing binary operator before token '('
    63 |     #if __has_builtin (__builtin_unreachable)

Both branches removed here only exist for non-GNU compilers (nested
under, or parallel to, "#ifdef __GNUC__"), and this project only ever
builds EDK2 with GCC (aarch64-poky-linux-gcc), where __GNUC__ is
always defined for real C compiles - so the __has_feature branches
are dead code for us either way, in both normal and assembler-with-cpp
preprocessing. The ANALYZER_NORETURN block hits the same parse error
independent of assembler-with-cpp mode too, since its outer guard is a
bare "#ifdef __has_feature" (no __GNUC__ exclusion), and
"#if __has_feature (...)" isn't parseable there either.

Dropping both branches doesn't change UNREACHABLE()/ANALYZER_NORETURN
for GCC: __builtin_unreachable() still comes from the __GNUC__ branch,
and ANALYZER_NORETURN still resolves to its pre-existing empty-macro
default either way (GCC doesn't have the clang-only
"analyzer_noreturn" attribute).

